  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, \"nang\" and \"ng\" are both important particles, but they serve different purposes and are used in different contexts. Here are the rules for using each:\n\n### **Ng**\n1. **Genitive Marker**: \"Ng\" is used to indicate possession or to show that something belongs to someone or something. \n   - Example: \"Aklat ng bata\" (Book of the child).\n\n2. **Direct Object Marker**: It is also used before a noun that serves as the direct object of a verb.\n   - Example: \"Kumain siya ng saging\" (He/She ate a banana).\n\n3. **Used with Nouns**: \"Ng\" is typically used with nouns.\n   - Example: \"Pusa ng kapitbahay\" (Cat of the neighbor).\n\n### **Nang**\n1. **Adverbial Marker**: \"Nang\" often serves as a connector to indicate the manner of an action or to modify a verb.\n   - Example: \"Tumakbo siya nang mabilis\" (He/She ran quickly).\n\n2. **Time Marker**: It can also indicate time or duration.\n   - Example: \"Nang dumating siya, umalis na ako\" (When he/she arrived, I had already left).\n\n3. **Used with Verbs and Adjectives**: \"Nang\" is used with verbs or adjectives rather than nouns.\n   - Example: \"Nag-aral siya nang mabuti\" (He/She studied well).\n\n4. **As a Conjunction**: \"Nang\" can also be used to connect clauses, similar to \"when\" in English.\n   - Example: \"Nang makita ko siya, natutuwa ako\" (When I saw him/her, I was happy).\n\n### **Summary**\n- Use **\"ng\"** for possession and direct objects.\n- Use **\"nang\"** for manner of action, time, and to connect clauses.\n\nUnderstanding these rules will help you use \"nang\" and \"ng\" correctly in sentences!",
